data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for your test:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);  // or CollectionAssert.That is not built-in,
    // so use:
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    // For a predicate check, MSTest doesn't have a built-in "All match predicate",
    // but you can use:
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key MSTest replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(a, b)` |

**`CollectionAssert` members worth knowing:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)`
- `CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(collection, item)`
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — any order

The biggest win is `Assert.AreEqual` over `Assert.IsTrue` for comparisons — on failure it shows *expected vs actual* values instead of just "expected true, got false."
